Helpfulness of Amazon Digital Video Game Reviews - An Application of SHAP on NLP¶

1. Highlights¶

  1. The scope of explainability require different approaches. What works locally may not work globally.
  2. Global explainations are better done with tokens clustered into topics.
  3. Local explainations are better without decomposition for simpler models.
  4. The easiest local explanation is the addition of token weights.
  5. The Pipeline class can handle vectorization and decomposition in succession.

2. Introduction¶

Effective online merchant platforms often employ a review system to improve customer relations by being able to rate their products. Reviews give other customers more information for their evaluation and purchase. Platforms regulate their reviews through different methods such as manual review or a voting system such as that of Amazon.

Video games specifically rely heavily on reviews to sell due to the worth of games being correlated to the experience of playing it. In most cases, you can't experience the game unless you buy it so people will generally look to reviews of those who have already experienced or bought the game.

Review helpfulness can be measured as the comprehensiveness and relevance of its content, regardless of length. On Amazon, customers can vote on a review as helpful or not. In this project, the goal is to determine any themes that may arise from helpfulness and if possible be able to determine how an individual review is helpful. [1]

3. Motivation and Business Value¶

Improving a platform's review helpfulness retains more customers and increases sales. It also improves the overall helpfulness of the platform and in turn, helps customer perception and decision-making behavior which may also increase sales. [1]

Knowing what makes reviews helpful such as product worth or the experience with the product helps the platform highlight and generate more helpful reviews. Platforms usually have sorting for reviews and the most helpful reviews can be boosted for more visibility. Content guidelines for the platform can be set using this knowledge which help generate more helpful reviews. [1]

4. Methodology¶

In [5]:
Image('Methodology - Global.png')
Out[5]:
Figure 1. Global explainability methodology.

Depending on the scope of explainability, the methodology used differs.

For global explainability, we use the pipeline above.

  1. Vectorize text data. The review data needs to be vectorized to be able to pass it through a model. TF-IDF was the chosen model due to token (words) weights being scaled against its importance in the whole corpus.
  2. Latent Semantic Analysis. Latent Semantic Analysis (LSA) is the application of Singular Value Decomposition (SVD) on text data to determine the underlying topics in the corpus.
  3. Model Selection and Hyperparameter Tuning. This is considered as a classification problem, thus classification mdoels were used and tuned.
  4. Explainability with SHAP. Summary Plots were used to produce the topics. The most prominent words under each were then interpreted.
In [3]:
Image('Methodology - Local.png')
Out[3]:
Figure 2. Local explainability methodology.

Depending on the scope of explainability, the methodology used differs.

For local explainability, it shares similar steps with global except for LSA so that words are not grouped into topics and we can see how words contribute to the prediction. LSA also allows for words to be shared in different topics which makes interpreting individual reviews harder.

  1. Vectorize text data.

  2. Model Selection and Hyperparameter Tuning

  3. Explainability with SHAP

Force plots for sample reviews were created and interpreted .

Dataset Description¶

The dataset was scraped from Amazon and is available on Jojie. The products are under the Digital Video Games category. It is composed 144724 reviews from 2006 to 2015. The columns we will mainly be looking at are helpful_votes, verified_purchase, review_body and review_date.

Variable Description
helpful_votes The sum of all votes of whether a customer found a review helpful or not. A customer can only upvote a review and has only one vote per review.
verified_purchase Variable describing whether or not a purchase was verified or received by the customer.
review_body The actual text content of the review.
review_date The date the review was posted.

6. Data Cleaning¶

Filtering¶

Because we will be dealing with text data, it would be best to reduce the dataset else we will have unreasonably long run times.

  1. Only verified purchases were considered as these would be the only legitimate reviews.
  2. Review dates from 2013 onwards only were considered.
  3. Only reviews with at least one helpful vote were considered. The rationale is to remove the bias of unseen reviews being marked as unhelpful. The dataset also has a majority of zero helpful votes. In this way, with at least 1 vote, we can say that a review was seen but not heplful enough for other users, hence they did not vote more on it. Users are capable of giving large numbers of votes based on the distribution of votes in the next section. It would be apt to call the class least helpful rather than unhelpful.

Preprocessing Functions¶

Text needs to be preprocessed before being vectorized. This involves cleaning of unwanted symbols, making everything lowercase, removing stopwords (common English words), and lemmatizing the words (mapping them to their root word). [2]

In [36]:
#convert to lowercase, strip and remove punctuations
def preprocess(text):
    text = text.lower() 
    text = text.strip()  
    text = re.compile('<.*?>').sub('', text) 
    text = re.compile('[%s]' % re.escape(string.punctuation)).sub(' ', text)  
    text = re.sub('\s+', ' ', text)  
    text = re.sub(r'\[[0-9]*\]',' ',text) 
    text = re.sub(r'[^\w\s]', '', str(text).lower().strip())
    text = re.sub(r'\d',' ',text) 
    text = re.sub(r'\s+',' ',text) 
    return text

# remove stopwords
def stopword(string):
    a = [i for i in string.split() if i not in stopwords.words('english')]
    return ' '.join(a)

# lemmatization
# Initialize the lemmatizer
wl = WordNetLemmatizer()
def lemmatizer(string):
    
    def get_wordnet_pos(tag):
        if tag.startswith('J'):
            return wordnet.ADJ
        elif tag.startswith('V'):
            return wordnet.VERB
        elif tag.startswith('N'):
            return wordnet.NOUN
        elif tag.startswith('R'):
            return wordnet.ADV
        else:
            return wordnet.NOUN
    
    word_pos_tags = nltk.pos_tag(word_tokenize(string))
    a = [wl.lemmatize(tag[0], get_wordnet_pos(tag[1]))
         for idx, tag in enumerate(word_pos_tags)]
    if len(a) > 2:
        return " ".join(a)

# final preprocessing function
def finalpreprocess(string):
    return lemmatizer(stopword(preprocess(string)))

In [39]:
cols = ['mean_test_score', 'params']
def classify_linear(model, X, y):
    start_time = time.time()

    # hyperparameters
    alpha_range = [1e-3, 0.01, 0.1, 1, 100, 1000]
    if model[0] == 'LogReg':
        params = {model[0]+'__C': alpha_range}
    else:
        params = {model[0]+'__alpha': alpha_range}

    # cross-validation settings
    kf = KFold(n_splits=5)

    # vectorizer
    vectorizer = ('vectorizer', TfidfVectorizer(stop_words='english',
                                                max_df=0.7, min_df=0.001))
    pipeline = Pipeline([vectorizer, model])

    # gridsearch
    cv = GridSearchCV(estimator=pipeline, param_grid=params, cv=kf,
                      scoring='recall').fit(X, y)
    res = pd.DataFrame(cv.cv_results_, columns=cols)
    res = res.loc[cv.best_index_]
    res['time'] = (time.time() - start_time)
    return res.values

def classify_tree(model, X, y):
    start_time = time.time()

    # hyperparameters
    features_tuning = [0.1, 0.2, 0.5, 0.8]
    params = {model[0]+'__max_features': features_tuning}

    # cross-validation settings
    kf = KFold(n_splits=5)

    # scaler
    vectorizer = ('vectorizer', TfidfVectorizer(stop_words='english',
                                                max_df=0.7, min_df=0.001))
    pipeline = Pipeline([vectorizer, model])

    cv = GridSearchCV(estimator=pipeline, param_grid=params, cv=kf,
                      scoring='recall').fit(X, y)
    res = pd.DataFrame(cv.cv_results_, columns=cols)
    res = res.loc[cv.best_index_]
    res['time'] = (time.time() - start_time)
    return res.values

The classification models considered were Logistic Regression, Stochastic Gradient Descent Classifier, Random Forest (which is now commented out for reproducibility as it takes about 45mins to train), Gradient Boosting Method and Gaussian Naive Bayes.

Connecting with the rationale in filtering, the test score is recall. Since technically all reviews have at least one helpful vote, there is a reason to say all are relevant. Thus, being able to identify the true positives or relevant data out was the metric of choice.

The data was first split into train and test sets before they were vectorized. This is implemented using the Pipeline class in sklearn. Including the vectorization in the train test split reduces information of test set bleeding into the train set although it will increase run time.

Select best model¶

The best model is the SGD Classifier with a test score of 0.80. SGD Classifier is a regularized linear model with stochastic gradient descent learning. With some hyperparameter settings, it will act like a linear Support Vector Machine (SVM).

Interpretations:

  • Brand names such as amazon, steam and ea top the list. These words increase the helpfulness of a review.
  • wait can refer to either waiting off to buy the game. Wait times in downloading or playing online (including 'server') can also be relevant. This is also considered helpful for other customers to know.

For global explainability, it would be better to group words as manually clustering them based on their definitions is inefficient and time consuming. This pipeline is better to be used in Local explainability.

Local Explainability¶

In natural language processing, the easiest and most common way to determine local explainability is to get the cumulative weights of tokens in a certain document. Luckily, this is how SHAP already does local explainability using the Force plot however it uses shapley values instead of just the feature weights.

The visualizations below can also be accomplished using the plot.text SHAP function. However this requires the use of models and libraries outside of the scope of the project.

In [71]:
def print_shap_contrib(review, shpvs):

    feature_importance = pd.DataFrame(list(zip(shpvs, vocab)),
                                      columns=['shap_vals', 'word'])
    feature_importance.sort_values(by=['shap_vals'], ascending=False, inplace=True)
    feature_importance = feature_importance.head(30).append(feature_importance.tail(30))
    feature_importance = feature_importance.set_index('word')
    text = ''
    for i in review.split():
        if i in feature_importance.index:
            if feature_importance.loc[i]['shap_vals'] > 0:
                text += (Fore.RED + Style.BRIGHT + i)
            else:
                text += (Fore.BLACK + Style.RESET_ALL + i)
        else:
            text += (Fore.BLACK + Style.RESET_ALL + i)
        text += ' '
    print(text)

11. Including Latent Semantic Analysis in the Pipeline¶

In terms of global explainability, it is better to include LSA in the pipeline. This allows for underlying topics to emerge from the corpus. According to sklearn documentation, the recommended number of components for LSA is n = 100.

In [74]:
cols = ['mean_test_score', 'params']
def classify_linear(model, X, y):
    start_time = time.time()

    # hyperparameters
    alpha_range = [1e-3, 0.01, 0.1, 1, 100, 1000]
    if model[0] == 'LogReg':
        params = {model[0]+'__C': alpha_range}
    else:
        params = {model[0]+'__alpha': alpha_range}

    # cross-validation settings
    kf = KFold(n_splits=5)

    # vectorizer
    vectorizer = ('vectorizer', TfidfVectorizer(stop_words='english',
                                                max_df=0.7, min_df=0.001,
                                                sublinear_tf=True, use_idf=True))
    svd = ('svd', TruncatedSVD(n_components=100, random_state=42))
    pipeline = Pipeline([vectorizer, svd, model])

    # gridsearch
    cv = GridSearchCV(estimator=pipeline, param_grid=params, cv=kf,
                      scoring='recall').fit(X, y)
    res = pd.DataFrame(cv.cv_results_, columns=cols)
    res = res.loc[cv.best_index_]
    res['time'] = (time.time() - start_time)
    return res.values

def classify_tree(model, X, y):
    start_time = time.time()

    # hyperparameters
    features_tuning = [0.1, 0.2, 0.5, 0.8]
    params = {model[0]+'__max_features': features_tuning}

    # cross-validation settings
    kf = KFold(n_splits=5)

    # scaler
    vectorizer = ('vectorizer', TfidfVectorizer(stop_words='english',
                                                max_df=0.7, min_df=0.001,
                                                sublinear_tf=True, use_idf=True))
    svd = ('svd', TruncatedSVD(n_components=100, random_state=42))
    pipeline = Pipeline([vectorizer, svd, model])

    cv = GridSearchCV(estimator=pipeline, param_grid=params, cv=kf,
                      scoring='recall').fit(X, y)
    res = pd.DataFrame(cv.cv_results_, columns=cols)
    res = res.loc[cv.best_index_]
    res['time'] = (time.time() - start_time)
    return res.values

We see that by using SHAP and LSA, we improved our global explainability. We see that topics can determine helpfulness. Let's look at some topics and how they positively affect the model.

Topic #1: game, play, download, work, like, great, buy, time, good, fun

Topic 1 represents the general customer experience of the video game from purchase to play. Reviews with this topic will positively influence its helpfulness.

Topic #2: code, work, download, amazon, buy, steam, money, purchase, waste, refund

Topic 2 represents the financial worth of the game. Money, puchase, waste and refund all refer to purchasing the game and is very helpful for other customers because it gives them more information that cannot be immediately seen unless you play the game.

13. Conclusion¶

SHAP is a powerful library that allows for both local and global scope of explainability. However, when dealing with text data, there can be different approaches in local and global explainability.

Global explainability methods benefit from decomposition methods as the underlying themes are more representative of the corpus rather than manually clustering the words by interpretation. In terms of digital video games, topics such as the general experience and worth of the game positively contribute to its helpfulness. Therefore, these are the kidns of reviews that should be boosted on the platform. These topics can also be set as preferred talking points in the platform's content guidelines to generate better reviews.

For local explainability, the use of decompostiion methods such as LSA may reduce the individual token interpretability as they are hidden behind topics. A pipeline like this also means that the original document goes through more transformations which may render the meaning incomprehensible at the end. The model allows for a single review to go through only one transformation and be identified as helpful or not. This can be an added filter to helpful votes to verify if the review with a lots of votes is actually helpful.

14. Recommendations¶

  1. Models which capture token relationships better such as neural networks will give better test scores, thus better explainability in SHAP. These models may also be compatible with SHAP's plot.text function which offers a better visualization than manually coding.
  2. Other methods of decomposition may be employed to give better test scores. A higher number of components may improve the score as well however may increase run time further.
  3. Using other metrics may also be considered in training such as F1-score or AUC-ROC.
  4. Clustering of topics/tokens may also be done as the summary plot of SHAP allows this. However, this was not employed in this study due to the high dimensionality of the dataset and the increase in run time.
  5. Improving the target definition such as using multiple levels of helpfulness based on the number of votes or even pivoting to a regression problem by the number of votes may be employed to improve the model.
  6. Incorporating star rating and number of purchases in the dataset may also improve the model in determining helpfulness and may give more granular analysis in results.
